<div class="breadcrumb"><a href="">Home</a> &raquo; <a href="forum">forums</a> &raquo; <a href="forum/1">LtU Forum</a></div><h2>Derivation trees for lambda-calculus</h2>
<!-- begin content -->
<div class="node">
 <div class="content">
<p >Hi,<br >
I am studying lambda-calculus (untyped and typed). My teacher often uses the derivation trees.</p>
<p >For the untyped lambda calculus, such a tree has the following properties:</p>
<p >Starting from any lambda term T, we have:<br >
(I use \ for lambda)<br >
- if T=x, we build a terminal leaf node with label x</p>
<p >- if t=\x.M, we build a node with label \x with just one son, which is the subtree obtained applying the definition on M</p>
<p >- if T=(MN), we build a node with label @ with two sons. These are the subtrees obtained applying the definition on M and N.</p>
<p >This is not difficult, but I can't find examples of these trees on internet.</p>
<p >For the typed lambda calculus I can't really understand the method to check if a term is well typed or to assign a type to a term. I mean, using the tree system.</p>
<p >Do you know any good source where I can learn how these trees work?</p>
<p >Thanks,<br >
Carlo</p> </div>
 <div class="links">By <a href="user/4674" title="View user profile.">ilSignorCarlo</a> at 2007-11-26 22:01 | <a href="taxonomy/term/1">LtU Forum</a> | <a href="node/2549" title="foundations for J, APL etc">previous forum topic</a> | <a href="node/2543" title="A survey and discussion of taming effects">next forum topic</a> | <a href="http://www.technorati.com/search/lambda-the-ultimate.org/node/2545" title="Technorati search of other blogs commenting on this post.">other blogs</a> | 798 reads</div>
</div>
